How ADW Live Rating works

ADW Live Rating ranks agility teams (handler + dog) based on their results at international competitions. Think of it like a chess rating, but for agility — the more you compete and the better you place, the higher your rating climbs.

The big picture

The system processes competitions in chronological order. For every run (a single round in a competition), it looks at how each team placed relative to everyone else in that run. Teams that beat expectations — finishing higher than their rating would predict — gain points. Teams that underperform lose points. Over time, the rating converges on a team's true skill level.

Under the hood we use OpenSkill (Plackett-Luce), a modern statistical model similar to the Elo system used in chess, but designed for competitions where many participants are ranked at once (not just two players head-to-head).

Step by step

1. Collect results

We import results from international agility competitions. Each run is a single scored round — for example, "Individual Jumping Large, run 1" at EO 2024. A run must have at least 6 teams to count.

2. Process runs chronologically

Every team starts with the same default rating. Then, competition by competition and run by run, the algorithm updates all teams that participated:

  • Beat stronger opponents? Your rating goes up more.
  • Lost to weaker opponents? Your rating goes down more.
  • Eliminated (DIS/DSQ)? You're placed last in that run — it hurts your rating, but one bad day won't ruin everything.

The size of the rating change depends on how surprising the result was. A big upset causes a big swing; a predictable finish barely moves the needle.

3. Confidence grows over time

New teams start with high uncertainty — the system doesn't know yet how good they really are. With each run, uncertainty shrinks and the rating becomes more stable. Teams with very few runs are marked FEW RUNS to signal that their rating may still change significantly.

4. Podium bonus

Teams that consistently finish in the top 3 receive a quality bonus of up to +20% on their rating. Teams without any podium finishes get a small penalty (−15%). This rewards not just beating weak fields, but actually winning competitive runs.

5. Major event boost

Results from Major competitions (AWC, EO, JOAWC/SOAWC) carry 1.2× the weight of regular Open competitions. Winning a run at AWC moves your rating more than winning a run at a regional open.

6. Cross-size normalization

Each size category (Small, Medium, Intermediate, Large) is rated separately. Since some categories have more teams or tighter competition, we normalize the ratings so they are comparable across sizes. An average team in any category lands around 1500 points. This means you can compare a Small team's rating to a Large team's rating on the same scale.

What's included

  • Only runs from the last 730 days (~2 years) are counted — the rating reflects recent form, not lifetime history.
  • A team needs at least 5 runs in this window to appear in the rankings.
  • Both individual and team rounds count (using individual placements within team rounds).

Skill tiers

Based on where a team's rating falls within its size category:

TierWhat it means
EliteTop 2% — the absolute bestgold
ChampionTop 10% — consistently excellentpurple
ExpertTop 30% — above averageblue
CompetitorEveryone else — still competing at the international level!green

Reading the numbers

  • Rating ~1500 = average among ranked teams in that size category.
  • Rating ~1650 = clearly above average (top ~16%).
  • Rating ~1800+ = exceptional, among the very best in the world.
  • Trend arrows (▲▼) show how a team's rank changed since the last competition was added.

Technical details

For those interested in the math:

rating = (1000 + 40 × (μ − 1.0 × σ)) × quality_factor

Where μ (mu) is the estimated skill, σ (sigma) is the uncertainty, and quality_factor is the podium bonus (0.85–1.05 based on top-3 finish rate).
